column168: DURING THE ROUTINE TRANSFER OF DRUMS FROM ONE TRAILER TO ANOTHER A DRUM WAS NOTICED LEAKING.  APPROXIMENTLY ONE GALLON OF SOLUTION ACCUMULATED ON THE LOADING DOCK.  THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM WAS SLIGHTLY DENTED APPARENTLY ALLOWI NG A SMALL HOLE TO DEVELOP DURING HANDLING.  THE DRUM WAS IMMEDIATLY OVERPA CKED AND THE LIQUID ABSORBED, SWEPT UP, AND PLACED IN A DRUM.  AFTER PERFOR MING A QUALITY CONTROL ANALYSIS ON THE MATERIAL, THE SOLUTION WAS DISCOVERE D TO BE A SPENT CHROME IRIDITE SOLUTION WITH A PH OF 6.  THE DRUM WAS RELAB LED HAZARDOUS WASTE LIQUID, N.O.S., NA9189 TO MORE ACCURATELY DEFINE ITS CO NTENTS.  THE SPILL RESIDUE AND SOLUTION WILL BE DISPOSED OF IN ACCORDANCE W ITH ALL FEDERAL AND STATE REGULATIONS.

column168: AT 4:30PM, 0/10/86 SECTION FOREMAN REPORTED A TANK CAR, RTMX 1406 (SULFUR C HLORIDE-UN 1828) LEAKING IN KCS RY. WALL ST. YARD, BEAUMONT, TEXAS. CAR WAS LEAKING AT THE DOME FROM LEFT PIPE. BEAUMONT FIRE DEPT., MOBIL CHEMICAL, T EXAS RAILROAD COMMISSION NOTIFIED. LEAK WAS STOPPED AT 8:30PM. CAR MOVED TO MOBIL CHEMICAL REPAIRS. ABOUT 10 GALS. OF CONTENTS LEAKED OUT OF CAR. LIME STONE WAS DUMPED ON SPILL AREA TO NEUTRAILEZ -- NO EVACUATION NECESSARY. SI TE OF SPILL WAS AGAIN INSPECTED MORNING OF 9/11/86 BY KCS TRAINMASTER, MOBI L CHEM. TEAM. FIRE DEPT. CALLED TO WASH AREA DOWN, THEN LIMESTONE WAS DUMPE D ON AREA AGAIN. ENVIRONMENTAL ENGR. R. J. CUNHA WAS NOT PLEASED WITH FINDI NGS. THEY HAVE AGREED WITH OCCIDENTAL TO REMOVED THE ROCK AND CONTAMINATED ROCK AND LIMESTONE. CONTAMINATED MATERIAL TO BE REMOVED BY CHEMICAL WASTE M ANGAMENT, INC. OF PT. ARTHUR. ONE RAILROAD EMPLOYEE BREATHED FUMES AND WAS EXAMINED BY DOCTOR AND LOST ONE DAYS' WORK. THREE RAILROAD EMPLOYEES WHO WE RE ALSO WORKING IN THE AREA WERE SENT TO THE DOCTOR FOR EXAMINATIONS FOR SA FETY PRECAUTION.

PACKAGE WAS REMOVED FROM SORTING OPERATIONS BECAUSE OF A STRAIN ON THE BOX. UPON INSPECTION OF THE CONTENTS, TWO (2) ONE (1) QUART GLASS BOTTLES WERE FOUND OF WHICH ONE (1) WAS BROKEN.  BOTH INNER GLASS BOTTLES WERE APPLIED WITH CORROSIVE LABLES.  THERE WERE NO MASRKINGS OR LABELS TO INDICATE THIS PACKAGE WAS A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL. THE PACKAGE ALSO DID NOT HAVE A SHIPPER'S CERTIFICATION.  IT HAS NOT BEEN DETERMINED WHICH CONTENTS OF THE TWO (2) O NE (1) QUART BOTTLES BROKE.  THE FEDERAL AVIATION ADMINISTRATION WAS CONTAC TED AT 404/763-7871 WHERE SPECIAL AGENT MICHAEL TERRELL PERFORMED AN INSPEC TION OF THE PACKAGE.  PACKAGE IS NOW BEING HELD FOR DISPOSITION.

ON 9/27/86 AT 11:00 AM THE B-2 YARD ASSIGNMENT DISCOVERED AND REPORTED TANK CAR GATX 31801 CONTAINING SODIUM HYDROXIDE AND SODIUM BOROHYDRIDE SOLUTION , A CORROSIVE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL, SPLASHING OUT FROM AROUND THE DOME WHEN T HE CAR WAS IN MOTION. THE TANK CAR WAS PLACED INTO THE NORTH END OF NO.10 T RACK NORTH YARD. THE TANK CAR WAS BEING SHIPPED BY MORTON THIOKOL VENTRON C ORP TO BEAR ISLAND PAPER CO.  AT 11:15 AM CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIDE OF THE INCI DENT AND THEY NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER.  AT 11:35 RICH DELUKA OF MORTON THIOKOL CALLED AND WAS ADVISED OF THE SITUATION. HE ADVISED HE WOULD GET IN TOUCH WITH HIS CO.'S ENVIRONMENTAL PEOPLE AND CALL BACK. THE SHIPPER'S ENVIRONMEN TAL MANAGER, MARK BOINSTEIN, CALLED AT 1:30 PM AND ADVISED HE WAS MAKING AR RANGEMENTS WITH O.H. MATERIALS CORP. AT 2:05 PM TIMOTHY MURPHY, O.H. MATERI ALS OPERAATIONS SUPERVISOR ADVISED HE WOULD BE AT ACCA YARD AT 4:00 PM. O.H .MATERIALS ARRIVED AT 3:50 AND ASKED IF THE CAR COULD BE MOVED TO A BETTER LOCATION FOR REPAIRS. THE CAR WAS MOVED TO THE NORTH END OF NO.20 TRACK IN THE NORTH YARD.  AN INSPECTION WAS MADE OF THE CAR.  MURPHY FOUND THE PROBL EM TO BE A RUPTURED PRESSURE DISK. THE DISK WAS REPLACED AND THE CAR MOVED BACK AND FORTH TO DETIRMIN IF THE PROBLEM HAD BEEN CORRECTED. THE PROBLEM W AS CORRECTED AND THE CAR WAS RELAESED TO GO BACK INTO SERVICE AT 5:30 PM.
